{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of altering water properties like salinity or temperature to control invasive Asian clams and Ponto-Caspian gammarids?",
  "relevant_summary": "For Asian clams, a controlled laboratory study in the USA found that temperatures of 36\u00b0C or higher killed Asian clams within or after four days (Action 1116). Regarding salinity, a controlled, replicated laboratory study conducted in the USA found that Asian clams were killed (100% mortality) when exposed to high salinities (18-34\u2030) (Action 1115). For Ponto-Caspian gammarids, temperature control showed effectiveness, as a controlled laboratory study from the UK found that heating water to >36\u00b0C killed all shrimps after 15 minutes exposure and at >43\u00b0C all shrimps died immediately (Action 1092). However, salinity control showed mixed results for gammarids, as one of two replicated laboratory studies (one controlled) in Canada and the UK found that increasing the salinity level of water killed the majority of invasive shrimp within five hours, while one found that increased salinity did not kill invasive killer shrimp (Action 1091).",
